Background Species: Cyanocitta stelleri [diademata Group] -- Steller's Jay (Southwest Interior)
Media notes: The Woodhouse's Scrub Jay is on the left, and a Steller's Jay is on the right. This photo shows a nice profile shape of a Scrub Jay.  The longer tail is consistent with a Scrub Jay versus the shorter tail of a Pinyon Jay.  The blue on the head, wings, undertail coverts, and in the tail is apparent, as is the grayish lower chest, belly,  and sides. A grayish mantle is also visible.  A faint blue breast band of the Woodhouse's Scrub Jay is also visible. The slightly darker grayish ear patch, and white/light gray steaky throat are readily apparent.
Observation Details: Both the Steller’s Jay and the Scrub Jay were on the feeder at the same time. Similarly sized, the Scrub Jay was a bluish - bluish-gray bird, no crest, relatively long tail (longer than a Pinyon Jay), faint blue breast band, and faint striping on the light gray/whitish throat. Photos to be attached. This is the first time I have seen a Woodhouse's Scrub Jay in this area.

My attention was on my coffee and my book when I suddenly heard a few loud, sort of hoarse and squeaky "Wheeeep! Wheeeep!" calls outside. I looked up only to find the Scrub Jay had returned. This time it hung around though, and I could admire it for a while. It had that same beautiful Titian blue back and wings that Florida Scrub Jays have; with a gray "cape" over its back. But this one had the same blue color all across its forehead, and a whiter, more pronounced "beard" going down its throat. I thought the belly looked a little darker too. Its voice was a little different from the Florida Scrub Jay's - it sounded more inquisitive in its squeaky "Wheeeep? Wheeeep?" calls (on a rising inflection) - as opposed to the Florida Scrub Jay's "sore throat".

**Very rare. First county record in eBird. We were walking through the wooded section when Joey spotted a jay in flight and quickly realized it was a Woodhouse's Scrub-Jay. It was quite shy and difficult to see in the open but I managed to take a few photographs and also some audio recordings. Since quite out of range, worth considering other subspecies but does seem to be the most expected A. w. suttoni. The next most expected could perhaps be A. w. texana of the Edwards Plateau, but these are readily distinguished by whitish undertail coverts. Nominate more similar to this bird, but should have grayer mantle (not as brown as this bird), undertail coverts less deep blue, and with more extensive pale supercilium.  This has been a very good irruption year for several species of mountain birds including Mountain Chickadees and finches.

Observation Details: Immediately noticed the dingy gray underparts of this bird and I also thought its call sounded more high-pitched than the CASJ calls I'm used to hearing. From the photos this looks like a textbook WOSJ, with the back relatively pale, the blue breast band relatively dull and with very indistinct edges, the white throat and breast contrasting strongly with the gray belly, and the white eyebrow stripe relatively thin and indistinct. The bill looks on the small side too relative to a typical CASJ. I have read that CASJs with worn plumage in late summer/early fall can resemble WOSJ, and this bird does show feather wear, but I assume even one of those CASJs would not look as much like a WOSJ as this bird does. CASJs are common at this location, but there do not seem to be any previous eBird records for WOSJ close to this site; the closest one is just east of Reno, at Hidden Valley Regional Park. Approximate location of the bird: 39.5606 -119.9049. Last seen flying roughly south down the canyon.

Locality: North of Randall Davey Audubon Center

Observation Details: My attention was on my coffee and my book when I suddenly heard a few loud, sort of hoarse and squeaky "Wheeeep! Wheeeep!" calls outside. I looked up only to find the Scrub Jay had returned. This time it hung around though, and I could admire it for a while. It had that same beautiful Titian blue back and wings that Florida Scrub Jays have; with a gray "cape" over its back. But this one had the same blue color all across its forehead, and a whiter, more pronounced "beard" going down its throat. I thought the belly looked a little darker too. Its voice was a little different from the Florida Scrub Jay's - it sounded more inquisitive in its squeaky "Wheeeep? Wheeeep?" calls (on a rising inflection) - as opposed to the Florida Scrub Jay's "sore throat".

Media notes: with prey

One of two Woodhouse's Scrub-Jays seen and here photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 2 May 2019 at the Baker sewage ponds, Baker, San Bernardino County, California.  One of these birds was presumably the same individual that had been reported without details on 29 April 2019 by Andrew Keaveney.  Although this species breeds in the mountains to the east, it is most unexpected on the desert floor.
Observation Details: Although I knew a Woodhouse's Scrub-Jay had been reported at the ponds a few days earlier, I was nevertheless when I heard "shreck" calls that were obviously those of a scrub-jay, a seemingly somewhat shriller and higher-pitched than those from the coastal population.  It took some effort, but we eventually managed to see one of these birds relatively well through my scope and Tom spotted a second bird as it flew in from the south.  Both birds were medium-sized passerines with conspicuously long tails, bluish coloration to the wings and tail, and pale grayish underparts.  I further noted on the bird that I saw best that the bill was relatively long and slim, with a weakly hooked tip.  This bird also had a relatively large head with a weakly rounded crown, a neck that was long enough to be conspicuous, a plump both with an upright posture. and a tail that was about as long as the head and body combined, somewhat flared at times, and seemingly rounded at the tip, at least when flared.  Tom also noted that the primary projection was quite short, but I did not see this in the field. I also noted through my scope that the head and the back and sides of the neck were mostly blue, but also with a pale supercilium that appeared to be quite narrow and whitish or pale gray in color.  The back was dingy grayish, but the wings and tail were blue, yet seemingly a lighter shade of blue than that characterizing a California Scrub-Jay.  The throat and underparts appeared to be dingy whitish to light gray and even though I saw diffuse grayish markings at the sides of the breast, this bird did not appear to have the conspicuous collar of a California Scrub-Jay.  The belly and flanks were paler than the sides of the breast, but they were not white, instead appearing to be light gray.  I did not see the undertail coverts overly well, but what I did see did not appear to be obviously bluish in color. I thought the bill was blackish, but i saw it only in the shade, and I likewise thought both the eyes and legs were dark, but I did not see either all that well.

Pics/vid/recordings. (33.7009048, -114.4979158). Big scrub jay, heard the jays call and realized it was rare so I drove over and got out and it was perched up in a bush near the river. Very responsive to WOSJ calls. The calls were not as bright and electric as CASJ calls. I got recordings of the “jay!!” call as well as the “cha-cha-cha-cha-cha!” call as it flew over. From reading afterwards the WOSJ call tends to be more disyllabic rather than more of a single syllable call for CASJ, which the spectrogram looks good for more of a 2 syllable call rather than one.  Blue crown/wings/tail, black face with thin white eyebrow, big black bill, gray below with whiter streaked throat, slight blue breast band but not as bright or bold as CASJ. I believe Woodhouse’s is more expected here? At least compared to california. In the field did not compare back vs underparts contrast. From looking at the pics afterwards also in the pics when the bird is sitting in the mesquite you can see the blue undertail coverts.
